The [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs]] has diagnosed more than 200,000 American veterans with [[PTSD]] since 2001.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Aikins |first1=Matthieu |last2=Koehler |first2=Chris |year=2013 |title=Mental Combat |journal=[[Popular Science]] |volume=282 |issue=3 |pages=40–45 |url=http://www.popsci.com/technology/article/2013-02/us-armys-ambitious-fight-against-ptsd |accessdate=15 February 2013}}</ref>

* Yemen

{{Main|Terrorism in Yemen}}

===Total terrorist casualties===
On December 7, 2015, the Washington Post reported that since 2001, in five theaters of the war (Afghanistan, Iraq, Yemen, Syria and Somalia) that the total number of terrorists killed ranges from 65,800 to 88,600, with the Obama administration being responsible for between 30,000 and 33,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2015/12/07/president-obama-likes-to-brag-about-the-terrorists-he-has-taken-out-how-many-is-that-exactly/|title=How many terrorists has President Obama actually 'taken out'? Probably over 30,000.|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=7 December 2015}}</ref>

==Costs==
The War on Terror, spanning decades, is a multi-trillion-dollar war.

According to the Costs of War Project at [[Watson Institute for International and Public Affairs|Brown University's Watson Institute]], the War on Terror will have cost $5.6 trillion for operations between 2001-2018 plus anticipated future costs of veterans' care.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Engelhardt|first1=Tom|title=America's 'War on Terror' Has Cost Taxpayers $5.6 Trillion|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/americas-war-on-terror-has-cost-taxpayers-5-6-trillion/|accessdate=20 May 2018|publisher=The Nation|date=18 May 2018}}</ref>

According to the Soufan Group in July 2015, the U.S. government was spending {{nowrap|$9.4 million}} per day in operations against ISIS in Syria and Iraq.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://soufangroup.com/tsg-intelbrief-terrorism-in-the-horn-of-africa/|title = TSG IntelBrief: Terrorism in the Horn of Africa|date = 2015-07-28|accessdate = 2015-07-28|website = The Soufan Group|publisher = |location = New York, NY}}</ref>

A March 2011 Congressional report<ref name="Daniel Trotta">{{cite news
|url = https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/06/29/us-usa-war-idUSTRE75S25320110629
|title = Cost of war at least $3.7 trillion and counting
|author = Daniel Trotta
|agency=[[Reuters]]
|date = 29 June 2011
|accessdate=25 June 2012
}}</ref> estimated war spending through the fiscal year 2011 at $1.2 trillion, and future spending through 2021 (assuming a reduction to 45,000 troops) at $1.8 trillion. A June 2011 academic report<ref name="Daniel Trotta"/> covering additional areas of war spending estimated it through 2011 at $2.7 trillion, and long-term spending at $5.4 trillion including interest.<ref group="note">Among costs not covered by these figures are off-[[United States Department of Defense|DoD]] spending beyond 2012, economic opportunity costs, state and local expenses not reimbursed by the federal government, nor reimbursements made to foreign coalition allies for their expenses.</ref>

